<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="200" pageId="7" pageNumber="199" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1864,2035]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,393]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="200" pageId="7" pageNumber="199">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1936,1962]" pageId="7" pageNumber="199">Remarks.</emphasis>
The white tomentose maculae on the elytron of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1873" box="[868,1107,1936,1962]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="199" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verlorenii">
<emphasis box="[868,1107,1936,1962]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="199">Platysodes verlorenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are fairly varying in number and size (
<figureCitation box="[263,403,1972,1998]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[167,1417,190,1753]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[164,1423,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Specimens of Platysodes verlorenii Westwood, 1873. 18–22, variability of maculae of elytron: 18, one indistinct macula (slightly greasy, BMNH); 19, macula absent (CKSJ); 20, two indistinct maculae (slightly greasy, CKSJ); 21, two distinct maculae (NHMB); 22, three distinct maculae (CKSJ). 23, distal declivity of elytra (MNHN). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301821/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="199">Figs. 18–22</figureCitation>
). Apart from the specimens bearing two or three maculae on elytron mentioned in 
<bibRefCitation author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." pageId="7" pageNumber="199" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="199">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
, elytron with a single macula also can be observed in a few individuals (
<figureCitation box="[1092,1175,2008,2034]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[167,1417,190,1753]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[164,1423,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Specimens of Platysodes verlorenii Westwood, 1873. 18–22, variability of maculae of elytron: 18, one indistinct macula (slightly greasy, BMNH); 19, macula absent (CKSJ); 20, two indistinct maculae (slightly greasy, CKSJ); 21, two distinct maculae (NHMB); 22, three distinct maculae (CKSJ). 23, distal declivity of elytra (MNHN). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301821/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="199">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
), even the maculae are entirely absent (
<figureCitation box="[331,414,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[167,1417,190,1753]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[164,1423,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Specimens of Platysodes verlorenii Westwood, 1873. 18–22, variability of maculae of elytron: 18, one indistinct macula (slightly greasy, BMNH); 19, macula absent (CKSJ); 20, two indistinct maculae (slightly greasy, CKSJ); 21, two distinct maculae (NHMB); 22, three distinct maculae (CKSJ). 23, distal declivity of elytra (MNHN). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301821/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Our re-examination confirmed that the totally black female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1873" box="[1134,1271,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verlorenii">
<emphasis box="[1134,1271,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. verlorenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[151,251,187,213]" name="Thailand" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">Thailand</collectingCountry>
has been misidentified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Arrow, M. O. de Lisle" authorityYear="1910" box="[559,671,187,212]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jansoni">
<emphasis box="[559,671,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. jansoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakai, K." box="[719,865,187,213]" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref4793" refString="Sakai, K. (2001) Cetoniine beetles of Thailand. Saikaku Tsushin, 3, 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="2001">Sakai (2001)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[924,1119,186,213]" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[976,1035,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
since their appearances are rather similar. Moreover, 
<bibRefCitation author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[438,625,222,249]" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[487,544,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
noticed the presence of matt area in the elytral distal declivity of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. ver-lorenii</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[241,380,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[167,1417,190,1753]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[164,1423,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Specimens of Platysodes verlorenii Westwood, 1873. 18–22, variability of maculae of elytron: 18, one indistinct macula (slightly greasy, BMNH); 19, macula absent (CKSJ); 20, two indistinct maculae (slightly greasy, CKSJ); 21, two distinct maculae (NHMB); 22, three distinct maculae (CKSJ). 23, distal declivity of elytra (MNHN). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301821/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">Figs. 22–23</figureCitation>
); nevertheless, they suspected that this species is conspecific to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Arrow, M. O. de Lisle" authorityYear="1910" box="[1104,1214,259,284]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jansoni">
<emphasis box="[1104,1214,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. jansoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1990" box="[1270,1430,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis box="[1270,1430,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The examination of further materials shows this character is stable for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1873" box="[942,1078,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verlorenii">
<emphasis box="[942,1078,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. verlorenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which lets it distinctly different from the latter two. Conversely, this species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Qiu &amp; Xu, 2020" authorityName="Qiu &amp; Xu" authorityYear="2020" box="[759,912,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sabatinellii" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[759,912,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">P. sabatinellii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[918,1054,330,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[918,1054,330,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="200" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in elytron with white maculae and matt distal declivity (
<figureCitation box="[389,467,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[169,1416,191,1873]" captionTargetId="figure-17@2.[164,1423,179,1883]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Type specimens of Platysodes sabatinellii Qiu &amp; Xu, new species. 1–3, holotype (BMNH): 1, dorsal view; 2, ventral view; 3, oblique view. 4–5, parameres of paratype in lateral and apical view (Darjeeling, NHMB; provided by Guido Sabatinelli). 6, paratype (CKSJ). 7–8, allotype (MNHN): 7, dorsal view; 8, distal declivity of elytra. Red arrows emphasize the matt area." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301817/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">Figs. 3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[480,512,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–23" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1781,1805]" captionTargetBox="[167,1417,190,1753]" captionTargetId="figure-18@5.[164,1423,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18–23. Specimens of Platysodes verlorenii Westwood, 1873. 18–22, variability of maculae of elytron: 18, one indistinct macula (slightly greasy, BMNH); 19, macula absent (CKSJ); 20, two indistinct maculae (slightly greasy, CKSJ); 21, two distinct maculae (NHMB); 22, three distinct maculae (CKSJ). 23, distal declivity of elytra (MNHN). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301821" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301821/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="200">22</figureCitation>
). By the number of grooves on elytron, they can be readily differentiated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
